# ✅ Difference between `Object.freeze()` and `Object.seal()`

Both methods are used to **control modifications to objects**, but they differ in **how restrictive** they are.

***

## 🔹 Quick One‑Line Definitions

*   **`Object.seal()`** → Prevents **adding or removing properties**, but **allows modifying existing values**.
*   **`Object.freeze()`** → Prevents **adding, removing, or modifying properties** (fully immutable).

***

## ✅ `Object.seal()`

### 🔹 What it does

*   ❌ Cannot add new properties
*   ❌ Cannot delete existing properties
*   ✅ Can **modify existing property values**
*   ❌ Cannot change property descriptors

***

### ✅ Example

```js
const user = { name: "Raja", age: 30 };

Object.seal(user);

user.age = 31;        // ✅ allowed
user.city = "HYD";   // ❌ not allowed
delete user.name;    // ❌ not allowed

console.log(user);
```

### ✅ Output

```js
{ name: "Raja", age: 31 }
```

***

### ✅ Use Case

*   Object **structure must remain same**
*   Values may change
*   Example: config objects with mutable values

***

## ✅ `Object.freeze()`

### 🔹 What it does

*   ❌ Cannot add properties
*   ❌ Cannot delete properties
*   ❌ Cannot modify values
*   ❌ Cannot change property descriptors

✅ Object becomes **fully read‑only**

***

### ✅ Example

```js
const user = { name: "Raja", age: 30 };

Object.freeze(user);

user.age = 31;        // ❌ not allowed
user.city = "HYD";   // ❌ not allowed
delete user.name;    // ❌ not allowed

console.log(user);
```

### ✅ Output

```js
{ name: "Raja", age: 30 }
```

***

### ✅ Use Case

*   Immutable data
*   Constants
*   Redux initial state
*   Configuration that must never change

***

## 🔥 Side‑by‑Side Comparison

| Feature                | `Object.seal()` | `Object.freeze()` |
| ---------------------- | --------------- | ----------------- |
| Add new properties     | ❌ No            | ❌ No              |
| Delete properties      | ❌ No            | ❌ No              |
| Modify existing values | ✅ Yes           | ❌ No              |
| Change descriptors     | ❌ No            | ❌ No              |
| Immutability level     | Partial         | Full              |
| Strict mode error      | ✅ Yes           | ✅ Yes             |

***

## ✅ Strict Mode Behavior

```js
"use strict";

const obj = { a: 1 };
Object.freeze(obj);

obj.a = 2; // ❌ TypeError in strict mode
```

*   **Strict mode** → throws error
*   **Non‑strict mode** → fails silently

***

## ✅ Shallow Immutability (Important Interview Trap ⚠️)

Both `freeze()` and `seal()` are **shallow**.

```js
const obj = {
  user: { name: "Raja" }
};

Object.freeze(obj);

obj.user.name = "Ram"; // ✅ Allowed
```

✅ Only the **top‑level object** is frozen

***

### ✅ Deep Freeze Example

```js
function deepFreeze(obj) {
  Object.freeze(obj);

  Object.values(obj).forEach(value => {
    if (typeof value === "object" && value !== null) {
      deepFreeze(value);
    }
  });

  return obj;
}
```

***

## ✅ Useful Helper Methods

```js
Object.isFrozen(obj); // true / false
Object.isSealed(obj); // true / false
```

***

## ✅ Real‑World Usage (React / JS)

### ✅ `Object.freeze`

```js
const ACTIONS = Object.freeze({
  ADD: "ADD",
  REMOVE: "REMOVE"
});
```

✅ Prevents accidental change

***

### ✅ `Object.seal`

```js
const formData = Object.seal({
  name: "",
  email: ""
});

formData.name = "Raja"; // ✅
formData.age = 30;      // ❌
```

***

## ✅ Interview‑Ready Summary

> **`Object.seal()`** prevents adding or removing properties but allows modifying existing values, whereas **`Object.freeze()`** makes an object completely immutable by disallowing any changes.

***

## ✅ 10‑Second Interview Answer

> Freeze makes an object fully immutable, while seal only locks the structure but allows value updates.

